S1-001,Day 1,1,Song of Solomon 1:2,Let him kiss me with the kisses of his mouth—for your love is more delightful than wine.,"Kiss me and kiss me again, for your love is sweeter than wine.",Let him kiss me with the kisses of his mouth! For your love is better than wine;,Let him kiss me with the kisses of his mouth: for thy love is better than wine.,Let him kiss me with the kisses of his mouth—For your love is better than wine.,Love,Passionate,Reflect/Journal/Pray,"Do you still long for closeness with your spouse, or have you let routine dull that desire? What would it look like to lean back into affection and passion?",Pray for renewed desire,"Take a few quiet minutes to pray about your relationship, asking God to restore closeness, affection and desire between you. Be honest about where things have felt flat or routine.",Create a small moment of ease for them,Do one simple thing today that makes your spouse’s day feel a little easier or more enjoyable. Choose something specific to them rather than something generic.,Stay physically close for a few minutes,"Take 15–20 minutes to sit or lie close together and include intentional physical touch, like holding each other, a longer kiss or staying connected without distraction.","Create a relaxed, intimate space","Set aside at least an hour together where you can be physically close without rushing. Let yourselves enjoy touch, closeness and, if it feels natural, allow that to build into deeper intimacy."
S1-002,Day 2,1,Song of Solomon 1:9,"I liken you, my darling, to a mare among Pharaoh’s chariot horses.","You are as exciting, my darling, as a mare among Pharaoh’s stallions.","I compare you, my love, to a mare among Pharaoh’s chariots.","I have compared thee, O my love, to a company of horses in Pharaoh's chariots.","I have compared you, my love, to my filly among Pharaoh’s chariots.",Admiration,Passionate,Reflect/Journal/Pray,When was the last time your spouse truly stood out to you? What makes them different from everyone else in your eyes?,Let them know what sets them apart,"Think of one thing that makes your spouse different from everyone else, and share it with them in a natural moment today. Keep it specific so they can really feel it.",Do something thoughtful for them,"Choose one small, thoughtful action today that reflects what you admire about your spouse, like preparing something they enjoy or taking care of something for them.",Exchange appreciation,Take 15–20 minutes together and each share something you admire about the other. Let it land without brushing it off or turning it into a joke.,Enjoy being out together,Set aside at least an hour to go somewhere or sit somewhere you can simply enjoy each other’s company. Let appreciation come through the way you look at and respond to each other.
S1-003,Day 3,1,Proverbs 5:18,"May your fountain be blessed, and may you rejoice in the wife of your youth.",Let your wife be a fountain of blessing for you. Rejoice in the wife of your youth.,"Let your fountain be blessed, and rejoice in the wife of your youth.",Let thy fountain be blessed: and rejoice with the wife of thy youth.,"Let your fountain be blessed, And rejoice with the wife of your youth.",Joy,Passionate,Reflect/Journal/Pray,"Do you actively rejoice in your spouse, or have you started to take them for granted? What first drew you to them, and where do you still see that today?",Bring back something you love about them,Think back to earlier in your relationship and share one thing you loved about your spouse then that you still see now. Keep it simple and real.,Do something that lifts their mood,Look for an opportunity to brighten your spouse’s day in a small but meaningful way. Choose something that would genuinely make them feel good.,Choose something fun together,"Take 15–20 minutes to do something light and enjoyable together, like a short walk or sitting outside. Keep it easy rather than meaningful.",Return to something familiar,"Set aside at least an hour to revisit something you used to enjoy together. Focus on the feeling of being together, not recreating it perfectly."
S1-004,Day 4,1,Song of Solomon 1:15,"How beautiful you are, my darling! Oh, how beautiful! Your eyes are doves.","How beautiful you are, my darling, how beautiful! Your eyes are like doves.","Behold, you are beautiful, my love; behold, you are beautiful; your eyes are doves.","Behold, thou art fair, my love; behold, thou art fair; thou hast doves' eyes.","Behold, you are fair, my love! Behold, you are fair! You have dove’s eyes.",Admiration,Encouraging,Reflect/Journal/Pray,"Do you still notice your spouse’s beauty, both outwardly and inwardly? When was the last time you paused to really see them?",Put words to what you see,Notice something about your spouse’s character or presence today and express it to them. Keep it honest and specific.,Write it where they’ll find it,Take a moment to write a short note or message about what you appreciate in them as a person. Leave it somewhere they’ll come across it unexpectedly.,Slow down and be present,Take 15–20 minutes to sit together without distractions and stay engaged with each other. Let the moment unfold without rushing it.,"Create a calm, distraction-free environment","Set aside at least an hour where you remove distractions and create a calm space together, like dim lighting, music or a quiet setting, so you can focus fully on each other."
S1-005,Day 5,1,Song of Solomon 2:3,"Like an apple tree among the trees of the forest is my beloved among the young men. I delight to sit in his shade, and his fruit is sweet to my taste.",Like the finest apple tree in the orchard is my lover among other young men. I sit in his delightful shade and taste his delicious fruit.,"As an apple tree among the trees of the forest, so is my beloved among the young men. With great delight I sat in his shadow, and his fruit was sweet to my taste.","As the apple tree among the trees of the wood, so is my beloved among the sons. I sat down under his shadow with great delight, and his fruit was sweet to my taste.","Like an apple tree among the trees of the woods, so is my beloved among the sons. I sat down in his shade with great delight, and his fruit was sweet to my taste.",Love,Passionate,Reflect/Journal/Pray,"Does your spouse feel like a place of delight, comfort and sweetness to you? If that has faded, what may have crowded it out?",Let them know you enjoy them,Notice something about being with your spouse that you genuinely enjoy and share it in a natural way today. Keep it light and sincere.,Ease something for them,"Look for one small, practical way to take something off your spouse’s plate today. Make their day feel just a little lighter.","Create an easy, physical moment together","Take 15–20 minutes to sit or lie close together and allow physical touch to be part of the moment, whether that’s cuddling, holding each other or staying connected without distraction.",Slow down and enjoy each other physically,"Set aside at least an hour together where you can be relaxed and physically close. Let yourselves enjoy touch, closeness and, if it feels natural, allow that to build into deeper intimacy."
S1-006,Day 6,1,Colossians 3:12,"Therefore, as God’s chosen people, holy and dearly loved, clothe yourselves with compassion, kindness, humility, gentleness and patience.","Since God chose you to be the holy people he loves, you must clothe yourselves with tenderhearted mercy, kindness, humility, gentleness, and patience.","Put on then, as God’s chosen ones, holy and beloved, compassionate hearts, kindness, humility, meekness, and patience,","Put on therefore, as the elect of God, holy and beloved, bowels of mercies, kindness, humbleness of mind, meekness, longsuffering;","Therefore, as the elect of God, holy and beloved, put on tender mercies, kindness, humility, meekness, longsuffering;",Love,Gentle,Reflect/Journal/Pray,When have you been unkind or unforgiving to your spouse recently? What was really happening in your heart and mind when you did that?,Take a moment to reset your posture,"Take a few quiet minutes to reflect on your attitude toward your spouse today and ask God to help you respond with more patience, kindness and humility.",Take something off their plate,Choose one task your spouse would normally need to handle today and do it for them without being asked. Make their day feel lighter in a practical way.,Talk about how you’ve both been showing up,"Take 15–20 minutes together and gently share how you’ve each been feeling in the relationship lately. Keep it honest but kind, without blaming or defending.","Have a deeper, honest conversation","Set aside at least an hour to talk more openly about how you’ve both been feeling. Stay patient, listen well, and focus on understanding rather than fixing."
S1-007,Day 7,1,Song of Solomon 2:10,"My beloved spoke and said to me, “Arise, my darling, my beautiful one, come with me.”","My lover said to me, “Rise up, my darling! Come away with me, my fair one!”","My beloved speaks and says to me: “Arise, my love, my beautiful one, and come away,”","My beloved spake, and said unto me, Rise up, my love, my fair one, and come away.","My beloved spoke, and said to me: “Rise up, my love, my fair one, and come away.",Love,Passionate,Reflect/Journal/Pray,"When was the last time you invited your spouse into a moment of connection, fun or closeness? Are you still creating space for the two of you to step away from routine together?",Invite them into a moment,"At some point today, invite your spouse to step into a small moment with you, whether it’s sitting together, stepping outside or taking a short break. Keep it simple.",Create space for them to pause,Handle something practical for your spouse today so they have a moment to step out of their routine. Give them space without needing them to ask for it.,Take a short break together,Take 15–20 minutes to step away from whatever you’re both doing and spend that time together. Keep it light and focused on being present.,Step away from the usual,Set aside at least an hour to intentionally break out of your normal routine together. Go somewhere or do something that helps you reconnect outside of the everyday flow.
S1-008,Day 8,1,1 Corinthians 13:4,"Love is patient, love is kind. It does not envy, it does not boast, it is not proud.",Love is patient and kind. Love is not jealous or boastful or proud.,Love is patient and kind; love does not envy or boast; it is not arrogant.,"Charity suffereth long, and is kind; charity envieth not; charity vaunteth not itself, is not puffed up.","Love suffers long and is kind; love does not envy; love does not parade itself, is not puffed up.",Love,Encouraging,Reflect/Journal/Pray,"What does love mean to you in practice? What are all the ways you feel love, and show love, for your spouse?",Put your version of love into words,"Take a moment today to express what love looks like to you in action, either in a message or in person. Keep it grounded in real behaviour.",Show love in a practical way,Choose one specific action today that reflects patience or kindness toward your spouse. Let your actions match what you believe love is.,Compare how you experience love,Take 15–20 minutes together to share how each of you feels most loved in everyday life. Stay curious rather than trying to agree.,Try each other’s way of feeling loved,"Set aside at least an hour to intentionally show love in the way your spouse receives it best, even if it’s different from your natural style."
S1-009,Day 9,1,Song of Solomon 2:16,My beloved is mine and I am his; he browses among the lilies.,"My lover is mine, and I am his. He browses among the lilies.","My beloved is mine, and I am his; he grazes among the lilies.","My beloved is mine, and I am his: he feedeth among the lilies.","My beloved is mine, and I am his. He feeds his flock among the lilies.",Love,Passionate,Reflect/Journal/Pray,"Do you still feel chosen by your spouse, and do they feel chosen by you? What helps strengthen that sense of belonging between you?",Reinforce that you choose them,Let your spouse know in a simple way today that you choose them and value being together. Keep it natural and not over-explained.,Do something that supports your “us”,"Take care of something today that benefits both of you as a couple, like organising a shared task or preparing something that makes your time together easier.",Spend time reinforcing connection,Take 15–20 minutes together to check in on how connected you’ve both been feeling lately. Keep it open and without pressure.,Do something that reinforces your partnership,"Set aside at least an hour to do something as a team, like planning something together, organising part of your life or working toward a shared goal."
S1-010,Day 10,1,Song of Solomon 3:4,Scarcely had I passed them when I found the one my heart loves. I held him and would not let him go.,"Soon I found the one I love. I caught and held him tightly, then I brought him to my mother’s house.","Scarcely had I passed them when I found him whom my soul loves. I held him, and would not let him go.","It was but a little that I passed from them, but I found him whom my soul loveth: I held him, and would not let him go.","Scarcely had I passed by them, when I found the one I love. I held him and would not let him go.",Love,Passionate,Reflect/Journal/Pray,"Do you reach for your spouse and hold onto connection when you have the chance, or do you let those moments pass? What helps you stay emotionally and physically close?",Reach for connection today,"Make a conscious choice today to reach for your spouse, whether through a message, touch or shared moment, instead of letting the opportunity pass.",Remove something from their day,Notice one thing your spouse would normally need to do today and take care of it for them without being asked.,Hold onto the moment a little longer,"Take 15–20 minutes together and stay physically close, whether through holding each other, sitting close or lingering in touch longer than usual.",Create an evening of closeness,"Set aside at least an hour together where you prioritise physical and emotional closeness. Stay connected through touch, and allow that closeness to deepen naturally."
S1-011,Day 11,1,Song of Solomon 4:1,"How beautiful you are, my darling! Oh, how beautiful! Your eyes behind your veil are doves.","You are beautiful, my darling, beautiful beyond words. Your eyes are like doves behind your veil.","Behold, you are beautiful, my love, behold, you are beautiful! Your eyes are doves behind your veil.","Behold, thou art fair, my love; behold, thou art fair; thou hast doves' eyes within thy locks.","Behold, you are fair, my love! Behold, you are fair! You have dove’s eyes behind your veil.",Admiration,Encouraging,Reflect/Journal/Pray,"When was the last time you truly noticed your spouse and told them what you see in them? Not just generally, but specifically?",Call out something specific you notice,Notice one specific detail about your spouse today and point it out to them in a natural way. Make it something real rather than generic.,Respond to something they’ve done,"Notice something your spouse has done recently and respond with a practical action that acknowledges it, like supporting them or following through on something.",Spend time noticing each other,"Take 15–20 minutes together and intentionally pay attention to each other, whether through conversation or simply being present. Stay engaged rather than distracted.",Go somewhere and observe each other,"Set aside at least an hour to go out together or sit somewhere different, and pay attention to each other in that setting. Let your appreciation show naturally."
S1-012,Day 12,1,Song of Solomon 4:7,"You are altogether beautiful, my darling; there is no flaw in you.","You are altogether beautiful, my darling, beautiful in every way.","You are altogether beautiful, my love; there is no flaw in you.","Thou art all fair, my love; there is no spot in thee.","You are all fair, my love, and there is no spot in you.",Admiration,Passionate,Reflect/Journal/Pray,Do you focus more on your spouse’s flaws or their strengths? What would shift if you chose to see them through a lens of love and admiration more often?,Shift what you focus on,"Make a conscious effort today to focus on your spouse’s strengths rather than their flaws, and express one of those strengths to them.",Act in a way that affirms them,"Choose one action today that shows you value your spouse as they are, like supporting something important to them or easing a pressure they’re feeling.",Talk about what you value most,"Take 15–20 minutes together to share what you value most about each other. Keep it focused on appreciation, not comparison or fixing.","Create a positive, criticism-free space",Set aside at least an hour where you intentionally focus only on what you appreciate about each other. Keep conversation and tone affirming throughout.
S1-013,Day 13,1,1 John 3:18,"Dear children, let us not love with words or speech but with actions and in truth.","Dear children, let’s not merely say that we love each other; let us show the truth by our actions.","Little children, let us not love in word or talk but in deed and in truth.","My little children, let us not love in word, neither in tongue; but in deed and in truth.","My little children, let us not love in word or in tongue, but in deed and in truth.",Love,Light Stretch,Reflect/Journal/Pray,"Are there ways you say “I love you” out of habit, but don’t always back it up with action? What could that look like today?",Back up your words with action,"Think about something you often say but don’t always show, and take one step today to act on it. Keep it simple and real.",Follow through in a practical way,Choose one thing you know matters to your spouse and act on it without being asked. Let your actions speak clearly.,Compare words vs actions,Take 15–20 minutes together to talk about how each of you experiences love in action. Keep it open and curious rather than defensive.,Live out what you say,"Set aside at least an hour together and be intentional about showing love through what you do, not just what you say. Let your behaviour reflect what matters to each other."
S1-014,Day 14,1,Song of Solomon 4:9,"You have stolen my heart, my sister, my bride; you have stolen my heart with one glance of your eyes.","You have captured my heart, my treasure, my bride. You hold it hostage with one glance of your eyes.","You have captivated my heart, my sister, my bride; you have captivated my heart with one glance of your eyes.","Thou hast ravished my heart, my sister, my spouse; thou hast ravished my heart with one of thine eyes.","You have ravished my heart, my sister, my spouse; you have ravished my heart with one look of your eyes.",Love,Passionate,Reflect/Journal/Pray,"When was the last time you felt drawn to your spouse in a strong, emotional or physical way? What sparked that feeling?",Let attraction show,Notice a moment today where you feel drawn to your spouse and allow that to show through your words or tone. Don’t overthink it.,Make space for them to relax,Take care of something practical today so your spouse has more space to unwind. Let your action create ease for them.,Lean into that feeling together,"Take 15–20 minutes together and allow space for attraction or connection to build, whether through conversation, closeness or light touch.",Follow that connection further,"Set aside at least an hour together where you allow that sense of attraction to grow. Stay close, be present, and let intimacy develop naturally if it feels right."
S1-015,Day 15,1,Song of Solomon 4:10,"How delightful is your love, my sister, my bride! How much more pleasing is your love than wine.","How delightful is your love, my treasure, my bride! Your love is better than wine.","How beautiful is your love, my sister, my bride! How much better is your love than wine.","How fair is thy love, my sister, my spouse! how much better is thy love than wine!","How fair is your love, my sister, my spouse! How much better than wine is your love!",Love,Passionate,Reflect/Journal/Pray,"Do you still savour time with your spouse, or has it become routine? What would it look like to enjoy them more intentionally?",Express enjoyment in the moment,"When you notice yourself enjoying your spouse today, say it out loud rather than keeping it to yourself. Keep it simple and natural.",Create something they enjoy,"Do one thing today that you know your spouse enjoys, even if it’s small. Make the focus on their experience.",Stay in the moment together,Take 15–20 minutes together and resist the urge to rush or move on quickly. Let yourselves enjoy the time without needing to fill it.,Create an intentional “slow evening”,"Set aside at least an hour to slow everything down, like sharing a meal, sitting together or winding down without screens, and focus fully on enjoying each other."
S1-016,Day 16,1,Galatians 6:2,"Carry each other’s burdens, and in this way you will fulfill the law of Christ.","Share each other’s burdens, and in this way obey the law of Christ.","Bear one another’s burdens, and so fulfill the law of Christ.","Bear ye one another's burdens, and so fulfil the law of Christ.","Bear one another’s burdens, and so fulfill the law of Christ.",Goodness,Gentle,Reflect/Journal/Pray,"Is your spouse carrying something right now that you could step into and support them with? What might that look like in a simple, practical way?",Ask what they need most,"At a natural moment today, ask your spouse what would help them most right now, and listen without interrupting or jumping in with solutions.",Take one responsibility off them,Choose one specific task your spouse is carrying and handle it for them today without being asked. Remove that weight completely.,Create space for them to share,Take 15–20 minutes together and give your spouse your full attention to talk about what’s been on their mind. Focus on listening well.,Support them in a meaningful way,Set aside at least an hour to either help your spouse with something important to them or be present with them in a way that genuinely lightens what they’re carrying.
S1-017,Day 17,1,Song of Solomon 5:10,"My beloved is radiant and ruddy, outstanding among ten thousand.","My lover is dark and dazzling, better than ten thousand others!","My beloved is radiant and ruddy, distinguished among ten thousand.","My beloved is white and ruddy, the chiefest among ten thousand.","My beloved is white and ruddy, chief among ten thousand.",Admiration,Passionate,Reflect/Journal/Pray,What makes your spouse stand out to you above everyone else? When was the last time you told them that?,Put it into words clearly,"Tell your spouse what makes them stand out to you above everyone else, using your own words rather than something general.",Do something that reflects that admiration,"Choose one thoughtful action today that aligns with something you admire about your spouse, like supporting an interest or making something they enjoy.",Share what makes each other unique,Take 15–20 minutes together and talk about what makes each of you different and valuable. Keep it focused on appreciation.,Create an experience that celebrates them,"Set aside at least an hour to do something your spouse genuinely enjoys, where the focus is on them and what makes them who they are."
S1-018,Day 18,1,Song of Solomon 5:16,"His mouth is sweetness itself; he is altogether lovely. This is my beloved, this is my friend.","His mouth is sweetness itself; he is desirable in every way. Such, O women of Jerusalem, is my lover, my friend.","His mouth is most sweet, and he is altogether desirable. This is my beloved and this is my friend.","His mouth is most sweet: yea, he is altogether lovely. This is my beloved, and this is my friend.","His mouth is most sweet, yes, he is altogether lovely. This is my beloved, and this is my friend.",Love,Passionate,Reflect/Journal/Pray,Do you still see your spouse as both your partner and your friend? How do you nurture both parts of that relationship?,Acknowledge the friendship side,"Let your spouse know something you appreciate about them as a friend, not just as a partner. Keep it natural and unforced.",Do something that makes them smile,"Choose one simple, thoughtful action today that would brighten your spouse’s day in a light, friendly way.",Reconnect in a light way,"Take 15–20 minutes to talk, laugh or share something easy together. Keep it light rather than turning it into a deeper discussion.",Plan time that feels like friendship,"Set aside at least an hour to do something together that feels fun, relaxed and familiar, where you can enjoy each other without pressure."
S1-019,Day 19,1,Romans 15:2,"Each of us should please our neighbors for their good, to build them up.",We should help others do what is right and build them up.,"Let each of us please his neighbor for his good, to build him up.",Let every one of us please his neighbour for his good to edification.,"Let each of us please his neighbor for his good, leading to edification.",Goodness,Encouraging,Reflect/Journal/Pray,When did you last intentionally build your spouse up with your words or actions? What impact did that have?,Say something that lifts them up,Notice something about your spouse today and say something that genuinely builds them up. Keep it specific and real.,Support something that matters to them,"Do one practical thing today that helps your spouse move forward in something important to them, even in a small way.",Encourage each other openly,Take 15–20 minutes together to share what you respect and appreciate about each other. Keep it focused on encouragement.,"Create a positive, affirming environment",Set aside at least an hour where you intentionally keep your words and tone encouraging and supportive while spending time together.
S1-020,Day 20,1,Song of Solomon 6:3,I am my beloved’s and my beloved is mine; he browses among the lilies.,"I am my lover’s, and he claims me as his own. He feeds among the lilies.",I am my beloved’s and my beloved is mine; he grazes among the lilies.,"I am my beloved's, and my beloved is mine: he feedeth among the lilies.","I am my beloved’s, and my beloved is mine. He feeds his flock among the lilies.",Love,Passionate,Reflect/Journal/Pray,"Do you feel a strong sense of “us” in your relationship right now? If not, what might help rebuild that feeling?",Reinforce your connection in words,Let your spouse know something you value about being together as a couple and what “us” means to you right now.,Create something that strengthens your “us”,"Do one practical thing today that benefits your life as a couple, like organising something shared or preparing for time together later.",Check in on your connection,Take 15–20 minutes together to talk about how connected you’ve been feeling and what helps you feel close. Keep it open and relaxed.,Do something as a team,"Set aside at least an hour to do something together that requires you to operate as a team, like planning, organising or creating something shared."
S1-021,Day 21,1,Song of Solomon 7:6,"How beautiful you are and how pleasing, my love, with your delights!","Oh, how beautiful you are! How pleasing, my love, how full of delights!","How beautiful and pleasant you are, O loved one, with all your delights!","How fair and how pleasant art thou, O love, for delights!","How fair and how pleasant you are, O love, with your delights!",Love,Passionate,Reflect/Journal/Pray,"Do you still see your spouse as desirable and pleasing, or has familiarity dulled that for you? What would it look like to intentionally notice and appreciate them again?",Let your attraction show,"Notice something about your spouse today that you find attractive or pleasing and express it in a natural, genuine way.",Do something that makes them feel desired,"Take a small action today that makes your spouse feel wanted, like creating a moment for them to relax or setting up something they enjoy.",Create a moment of physical closeness,"Take 15–20 minutes to sit or lie close together and allow touch to be part of the moment, whether that’s holding each other or a longer kiss.",Lean into desire together,"Set aside at least an hour to be together in a relaxed, private space where you can enjoy being close and allow that attraction to build into deeper intimacy if it feels natural."
S1-022,Day 22,1,Proverbs 19:11,A person’s wisdom yields patience; it is to one’s glory to overlook an offense.,Sensible people control their temper; they earn respect by overlooking wrongs.,"Good sense makes one slow to anger, and it is his glory to overlook an offense.",The discretion of a man deferreth his anger; and it is his glory to pass over a transgression.,"The discretion of a man makes him slow to anger, and his glory is to overlook a transgression.",Self-control,Gentle,Reflect/Journal/Pray,Are there moments where you hold onto frustration or take offense more quickly than you need to? What would it look like to let that go more often?,Choose to let something go,Notice a moment today where you could take offense and consciously choose to let it pass without reacting.,Create a smoother moment for them,"Do one practical thing today that prevents friction or makes your spouse’s day easier, even if it’s something small.",Talk about how you handle frustration,Take 15–20 minutes together to share how you each respond to frustration and what helps you stay calm. Keep it honest but respectful.,"Create a calm, low-pressure evening",Set aside at least an hour together where the focus is on staying relaxed and not reacting quickly. Keep things light and let small things go.
S1-023,Day 23,1,Song of Solomon 7:10,"I belong to my beloved, and his desire is for me.","I am my lover’s, and he claims me as his own.","I am my beloved’s, and his desire is for me.","I am my beloved's, and his desire is toward me.","I am my beloved’s, and his desire is toward me.",Love,Passionate,Reflect/Journal/Pray,"Do you feel desired by your spouse, and do they feel desired by you? If that has faded, what part have you played in that shift?",Express desire directly,Tell your spouse in a simple and natural way that you desire them or enjoy being close to them. Keep it real rather than overthought.,Make space for connection later,Handle something practical today so you both have more time or energy to connect later. Remove a barrier.,Stay close and connected,"Take 15–20 minutes to be physically close, whether sitting, holding each other or sharing a moment without distractions.",Create time for intimacy,"Set aside at least an hour where you can be alone together without interruptions. Stay present, build closeness through touch, and allow intimacy or sex to develop naturally if it feels right."
S1-024,Day 24,1,Psalm 37:8,Refrain from anger and turn from wrath; do not fret—it leads only to evil.,Stop being angry! Turn from your rage! Do not lose your temper—it only leads to harm.,"Refrain from anger, and forsake wrath! Fret not yourself; it tends only to evil.","Cease from anger, and forsake wrath: fret not thyself in any wise to do evil.","Cease from anger, and forsake wrath; do not fret—it only causes harm.",Self-control,Gentle,Reflect/Journal/Pray,"When you feel frustration rise toward your spouse, how do you usually respond? What would it look like to pause and choose a different response in that moment?",Pause before reacting,"When you feel frustration rise today, take a breath and choose your response rather than reacting immediately.",Create space for a smoother day,Do something practical today that reduces pressure or tension in your shared environment. Think ahead and remove a trigger.,Reflect on how you respond,Take 15–20 minutes together to talk about how you each handle frustration and what helps you pause rather than react.,"Create a steady, calm space",Set aside at least an hour together where the focus is on being steady and present. Keep your tone calm and your responses intentional throughout your time together.
S1-025,Day 25,1,Song of Solomon 7:12,Let us go early to the vineyards to see if the vines have budded.,Let us get up early and go to the vineyards to see if the grapevines have budded.,let us go out early to the vineyards and see whether the vines have budded.,Let us get up early to the vineyards; let us see if the vine flourish.,Let us get up early to the vineyards; let us see if the vine has budded.,Joy,Passionate,Reflect/Journal/Pray,"When was the last time you intentionally created space to connect with your spouse, away from routine and responsibility? What tends to get in the way of that?",Express enjoyment of your time together,Take a moment today to tell your spouse something you genuinely enjoy about the time you spend together. Keep it simple and in-the-moment.,Make it easier to step away,Take care of something practical today so you can both step away from responsibilities more easily later.,Step out of routine briefly,"Take 15–20 minutes to step away from your usual routine together, even if it’s just going outside or changing environment.",Create a simple “escape” together,Set aside at least an hour to step away from your normal environment or routine. Go somewhere or create a different atmosphere so it feels like intentional time together.
S1-026,Day 26,1,1 Peter 4:8,"Above all, love each other deeply, because love covers over a multitude of sins.","Most important of all, continue to show deep love for each other, for love covers a multitude of sins.","Above all, keep loving one another earnestly, since love covers a multitude of sins.",And above all things have fervent charity among yourselves: for charity shall cover the multitude of sins.,"And above all things have fervent love for one another, for love will cover a multitude of sins.",Love,Encouraging,Reflect/Journal/Pray,"Has there been a time recently where you said something negative about your spouse to somebody else? If so, what could you have said instead, to have integrity in your speech about them?",Choose your words carefully today,"Be intentional about how you speak about your spouse today, both to them and about them. Choose words that reflect respect and love.",Do something that shows loyalty in action,"Take one practical step today that demonstrates you are for your spouse, like supporting them in front of others or handling something on their behalf.",Have an honest but kind conversation,Take 15–20 minutes together to talk about how you both feel when spoken about positively or negatively. Keep it respectful and grounded.,Create a space of trust and respect,Set aside at least an hour together where you are intentional about speaking well of each other and reinforcing trust through your words and tone.
S1-027,Day 27,1,Song of Solomon 8:6,"Place me like a seal over your heart, like a seal on your arm; for love is as strong as death.","Place me like a seal over your heart, like a seal on your arm. For love is as strong as death.","Set me as a seal upon your heart, as a seal upon your arm, for love is strong as death.","Set me as a seal upon thine heart, as a seal upon thine arm: for love is strong as death.","Set me as a seal upon your heart, as a seal upon your arm; for love is as strong as death.",Love,Passionate,Reflect/Journal/Pray,"How deeply committed do you feel to your spouse right now, not just in words but in your actions and focus? Where might your attention be divided?",Reaffirm your commitment in words,"Share something with your spouse that reflects your commitment to them, not just in general terms but in how you choose them daily.",Do something that shows you’re all in,"Take one practical action today that reflects commitment, like prioritising something important to them or following through on something you’ve said.",Talk about what commitment looks like,Take 15–20 minutes together to share what commitment means to each of you in everyday life. Keep it real and grounded.,Create time that reflects priority,Set aside at least an hour where your spouse is clearly your priority. Remove distractions and give them your full attention through your presence and focus.
S1-028,Day 28,1,Ruth 1:16,"Where you go I will go, and where you stay I will stay. Your people will be my people and your God my God.","Where you go I will go, and where you live I will live. Your people will be my people, and your God will be my God.","Where you go I will go, and where you lodge I will lodge. Your people shall be my people, and your God my God.","Whither thou goest, I will go; and where thou lodgest, I will lodge: thy people shall be my people, and thy God my God.","Where you go, I will go; and where you lodge, I will lodge; Your people shall be my people, and your God, my God.",Faithfulness,Encouraging,Reflect/Journal/Pray,How could you show your spouse that you love them unconditionally? How can you show them they are your one and only?,Put loyalty into words,"Express to your spouse in a simple way that you are with them, on their side, and committed to walking life alongside them.",Support their world in a practical way,"Do something today that supports your spouse’s life or responsibilities, like helping with something important to them or stepping into their world.",Share what “being a team” means,Take 15–20 minutes together to talk about how you show up as a team and where you could strengthen that. Keep it honest but encouraging.,Do something that strengthens your bond,"Set aside at least an hour to do something together that reinforces your sense of partnership, whether that’s planning, supporting each other or simply being present as a team."
S1-029,Day 29,1,Colossians 3:14,"And over all these virtues put on love, which binds them all together in perfect unity.","Above all, clothe yourselves with love, which binds us all together in perfect harmony.","And above all these put on love, which binds everything together in perfect harmony.","And above all these things put on charity, which is the bond of perfectness.","But above all these things put on love, which is the bond of perfection.",Love,Gentle,Reflect/Journal/Pray,"What does it actually look like, in your daily life, to “put on love” with your spouse? Where are you doing this well, and where could you step into it more intentionally?",Be intentional in how you show love,"Choose one way today to actively “put on love” in your behaviour, whether through patience, kindness or gentleness, and express that to your spouse.",Make their day easier again,Look for one practical way today to ease pressure for your spouse or take something off their plate without being asked.,Reflect on what love looks like in action,Take 15–20 minutes together to talk about how love shows up in your daily lives and what it looks like in real situations.,"Create a peaceful, unified space","Set aside at least an hour together where you focus on being calm, connected and unified. Let your actions and tone reflect love throughout your time together."
S1-030,Day 30,1,John 15:12,My command is this: Love each other as I have loved you.,This is my commandment: Love each other in the same way I have loved you.,"This is my commandment, that you love one another as I have loved you.","This is my commandment, That ye love one another, as I have loved you.","This is My commandment, that you love one another as I have loved you.",Love,Encouraging,Reflect/Journal/Pray,"Does your spouse know the depth of your love for them? Like, REALLY know? What have you said or done lately to show them that?",Say something that shows depth of love,Share something meaningful with your spouse that reflects the depth of your love for them. Let it go beyond surface-level words.,Do something that reflects sacrificial love,"Take one practical action today that puts your spouse first, even if it costs you time or effort.",Show appreciation openly,Take 15–20 minutes together to express appreciation and gratitude for each other and the relationship you’ve built.,Create a meaningful moment together,"Set aside at least an hour to intentionally mark this moment in your relationship. Do something that feels significant to both of you, and include closeness, affection or intimacy in a way that feels natural."